      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the paper **arXiv:2603.25839 — \"A Compression Perspective on Simplicity Bias\"**:\n\n### Paper Details\n\n- **Title:** A Compression Perspective on Simplicity Bias\n- **Authors:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Tom Marty, Eric Elmoznino, Leo Gagnon, Tejas Kasetty, Mizu Nishikawa-Toomey, Sarthak Mittal, Guillaume Lajoie, Dhanya Sridhar"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- **Submitted:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Thu, 26 Mar 2026"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- **arXiv ID:** 2603.25839 (cs)\n- **Link:** [https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.25839](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.25839)\n\n### Abstract Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Deep neural networks exhibit a simplicity bias, a well-documented tendency to favor simple functions over complex ones."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "In this work, the authors cast new light on this phenomenon through the lens of the Minimum Description Length principle, formalizing supervised learning as a problem of optimal two-part lossless compression."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Their theory explains how simplicity bias governs feature selection in neural networks through a fundamental trade-off between model complexity (the cost of describing the hypothesis) and predictive power (the cost of describing the data)."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The framework predicts that as the amount of available training data increases, learners transition through qualitatively different features — from simple spurious shortcuts to complex features — only when the reduction in data encoding cost justifies the increased model complexity."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nNote: The query mentioned \"Marty Elmoznino\" — these correspond to two of the authors: **Tom Marty** (first author) and **Eric Elmoznino** (second author)."
      }
    ],
